SPINNING RESERVE SERVICE AGREEMENT
This Spinning Reserve Service Agreement (“Agreement”) is made and entered into this 5th day of October, 2010 (the “Effective Date”), by and among Black Hills Power, Inc. (“Black Hills Power”), Cheyenne Light, Fuel and Power Company (“CLFP”), Black Hills/Colorado Electric Utility Company, LP (“Black Hills Colorado Electric”), and Black Hills Wyoming, LLC (“Black Hills Wyoming”), each of which may be referred to as a “Party” and collectively as the “Parties.” WHEREAS 1. Black Hills Power, CLFP, and Black Hills Colorado Electric each is a franchised public utility with captive customers and Black Hills Wyoming is a market-regulated public utility; and 2. Each Party owns and operates electric generating facilities that are capable of providing Spinning Reserve Service; and 3. Each Party may have an obligation to maintain generating reserves and from time to time has a need to procure Spinning Reserve Service from a third party supplier; and 4. From time to time it is not possible for a Party to procure Spinning Reserve Service from an unaffiliated third party supplier; and 5. The Parties wish to memorialize an arrangement under which a Party may procure Spinning Reserve Service from another Party at the providing Party’s cost of providing the service when (1) the Procuring Party cannot satisfy its entire reserve obligation using its own resources except by utilizing Capacity Resources that would have a higher cost or lower reliability than would be available through the procurement of Spinning Reserve Service under this Agreement, and (2) the Procuring Party cannot procure Spinning Reserve Service from an unaffiliated supplier; and 6. The Parties enter into this Agreement to allow each Party to provide a beneficial service to the other Parties that will allow the Parties to satisfy their reserve requirements and help maintain system reliability. NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the covenants and premises herein set forth, and other good and sufficient consideration, the Parties mutually agree as follows: ARTICLE I TERM OF AGREEMENT
1.1 This Agreement shall become effective on the Effective Date unless it is accepted by FERC effective on a later date, in which it shall become effective on such later date. 1.2 This Agreement shall continue in full force and effect from year to year until terminated by a Party upon six (6) months prior written notice to the other Parties or in accordance with Section 5.8. ARTICLE II DEFINITIONS For the purpose of this Agreement, the following definitions shall apply: 2.1 Agreement shall be this Agreement, including any attachments hereto, as the same may be amended, supplemented, or modified in accordance with its terms. 2.2 Capacity Resources shall mean those available Generating Units and firm purchased power resources owned or acquired by each Party. 2.3 FERC shall mean the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or its successor. 2.4 Generating Unit shall be an electric generator, together with its prime mover, and all auxiliary and appurtenant devices and equipment designed to be operated as a unit for the production of energy. 2.5 NS CT II Facility shall mean Black Hills Wyoming’s Neil Simpson Combustion Turbine II Generating Facility, a natural gas-fired electric generating facility. 2.6 Procuring Party shall be a Party that procures Spinning Reserve Service from another Party under this Agreement. 2.7 Spinning Reserve Service is generating service needed to serve load immediately in the event of a system contingency. 2.8 Supplying Party shall be a Party that supplies Spinning Reserve Service to another Party under this Agreement. 2.9 Wygen I Facility shall mean Black Hills Wyoming’s Wygen I Generating Facility, a coal-fired electric generating facility. ARTICLE III SPINNING RESERVE SERVICE 3.1 A Party may procure Spinning Reserve Service from another Party under the following circumstances: (a) The Procuring Party cannot satisfy its entire reserve obligation using its own resources without utilizing Capacity Resources that would have a higher cost or less reliability than would be available through the procurement of Spinning Reserve Service under this Agreement; and (b) The Procuring Party cannot procure Spinning Reserve Service from an unaffiliated supplier. 3.2 No Party shall be obligated to provide Spinning Reserve Service to another Party. 3.3 A Supplying Party may provide Spinning Reserve Service to a Procuring Party from any of its Capacity Resources, provided that the Parties acknowledge that due to Black Hills Wyoming’s existing joint ownership obligations with respect to the Wygen I Facility, Black Hills Wyoming will not provide Spinning Reserve Service from that facility but may provide Spinning Reserve Service from the NS CT II Facility. 3.4 A Party may procure Spinning Reserve Service for a period not to exceed one (1) month at a time. For the avoidance of doubt, a Party may procure Spinning Reserve Service for successive months, but only if the Party satisfies the criteria identified in Section 3.1 each time it procures Spinning Reserve Service. ARTICLE IV PRICE
A Supplying Party shall recover from the Procuring Party to which it supplies Spinning Reserve Service its actual cost of supplying the spinning reserves from the least cost option available to the Supplying Party at the particular time, which cost shall be determined after the Supplying Party satisfies (i) its load obligations and any other energy supply obligations at the time of its provision of Spinning Reserve Service, and (ii) its spinning reserve requirements and other spinning reserve supply obligations, if such obligations pre-date the effective date of this Agreement. When determining the Supplying Party’s actual cost of supplying Spinning Reserve Service under the preceding sentence, (x) if the Spinning Reserve Service is provided from Capacity Resources, the actual cost will equal the Supplying Party’s variable costs associated with supplying such Spinning Reserve Service plus the cost of energy associated with the production of spinning reserves plus actual start-up costs, and (y) if the Spinning Reserve Service is procured from a third party, the actual cost will equal the Supplying Party’s actual cost for the spinning reserves so procured. ARTICLE V GENERAL PROVISIONS 5. 1 Regulatory Authorization Black Hills Power will file this Agreement with FERC on behalf of all the Parties and request that it be accepted for filing as of the Effective Date. 5.2 Effect on Other Agreements This Agreement shall not modify the obligations of any Party under any other Agreement between or among the Parties that is in effect as of the date of this Agreement, or the obligation of others not party to this Agreement. 5.3 Billings Bills for services rendered under this Agreement shall be issued on a monthly basis for services performed during the preceding month. 5.4 Waivers Any waiver at any time by either Party of its right with respect to a default under this Agreement, or with respect to any other matter arising in connection with this Agreement, shall not be deemed a waiver with respect to any subsequent default or matter. Any delay, short of the statutory period of limitation, in asserting or enforcing any right under this Agreement, shall not be deemed a waiver of such right. 5.4 Successors and Assigns This Agreement shall inure to the benefit of and be binding upon the Parties only, and their respective successors and assigns, and shall not be assignable by any Party without the written consent of the other Parties. 5.5 No Third Party Beneficiaries This Agreement does not create rights of any character whatsoever in favor of any person, corporation, association, entity, or power suppliers, other than the Parties, and the obligations herein assumed by the Parties are solely for the use and benefit of said Parties. Nothing in this Agreement shall be construed as permitting or vesting, or attempting to permit or vest, in any person, corporation, association, entity, or power suppliers, other than the Parties, any rights hereunder or in any of the Generating Units or other assets owned by the Parties, or the use thereof. 5.6 Amendment This Agreement may be changed, amended, modified or supplemented only by an instrument in writing executed by all the Parties, which shall be effective after approval or acceptance for filing by FERC. 5.7 Liability and Indemnification Subject to any applicable state or federal law which may specifically restrict limitations on liability, each Party shall defend, indemnify, hold harmless, and release the other Parties, and their directors, officers, and employees, from and against any and all liability for loss, damage, or expense alleged to arise from, or incidental to, injury to persons, and/or damage to property in connection with its facilities or the production or transmission of energy by or through such facilities. In no event shall one Party be liable to the other Parties for any indirect, special, incidental, or consequential damages with respect to any claim arising out of this Agreement. 5.8 Regulatory Changes or Approvals. If any regulatory agency having jurisdiction over the Parties passes laws or regulations that make the obligations of this Agreement vary in any way other than that originally contemplated, then the Parties shall take such additional action as may reasonably be required to promptly comply with the change in law and obtain any additional required approvals. In the event such change or approval is not acceptable to a party, the objecting party may terminate this Agreement by three months prior written notice to the other party and after satisfaction of any and all outstanding obligations. 5.9 Governing Law The validity, interpretation and performance of this Agreement and each of its provisions shall be governed by the applicable laws of the State of South Dakota. 5.10 Section Headings The descriptive headings of the Articles and sections of this Agreement are used for convenience only, and shall not modify or restrict any of the terms and provisions thereof. IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the Parties have caused this Agreement to be executed and attested by their duly authorized officers on the day and year first above written. BLACK HILLS POWER, INC.

SCHEDULE 2 REACTIVE SUPPLY AND VOLTAGE CONTROL FROM GENERATION OR OTHER SOURCES SERVICE
In order to maintain transmission voltages on the Transmission Provider’s transmission facilities within acceptable limits, generation facilities and non-generation resources capable of providing this service that are under the control of the control area operator are operated to produce (or absorb) reactive power. Thus, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation or Other Sources Service must be provided for each transaction on the Transmission Provider’s transmission facilities. The amount of Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation or Other Sources Service that must be supplied with respect to the Transmission Customer’s transaction will be determined based on the reactive power support necessary to maintain transmission voltages within limits that are generally accepted in the region and consistently adhered to by the Transmission Provider. Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation or Other Sources Service is to be provided directly by the Transmission Provider or indirectly by the Transmission Provider making arrangements with the Control Area operator that performs this service for the Transmission Provider’s Transmission System. The Transmission Customer must purchase this service from the Transmission Provider. The charges for such service will be determined as set forth below. 1. The rates for service under this Schedule 2 include compensation to the Transmission Provider and other generators with annual revenue requirements on file with FERC for the recovery of their costs of supplying reactive power to the Transmission System through the capability of their generating resources to produce and provide reactive power within the power factor range of 0.95 leading and 0.95 lagging. The sum of such revenue requirements (adding that of the Transmission Provider to those of other such generators) is the “Aggregate Annual Reactive Revenue Requirement.” Funds received by the Transmission Provider for service under this Schedule 2 will be credited to all such generators, in proportion to their respective portion of the Aggregate Annual Reactive Revenue Requirement. If funds are owed to Schedule 2 customers pursuant to the true-up procedures set forth below, the funds owed will be debited to all such generators, likewise in proportion to their respective portion of the Aggregate Annual Reactive Revenue Requirement. 2. The Aggregate Annual Reactive Revenue Requirement is the sum of (a) the Transmission Provider’s annual reactive power revenue requirement, (b) the annual reactive power revenue requirement of the City of Gillette, Wyoming (“Gillette”), and (c) the applicable annual reactive power revenue requirements of other generators with annual reactive power revenue requirements on file with FERC for the provision of reactive power to the Transmission System. The Transmission Provider’s portion of the Aggregate Annual Reactive Revenue Requirement is $1,660,052. Gillette’s portion of the Aggregate Annual Reactive Revenue Requirement is $130,888. As of January 14, 2011, the portion of the Aggregate Annual Reactive Power Revenue Requirement attributable to other generators with annual reactive power revenue requirements on file with FERC for the provision of reactive power to the Transmission System is $861,446, comprised of the annual reactive power revenue requirement of Cheyenne Light, Fuel an Power Company on file with FERC in Docket No. ER09-1203-000 ($601,062) and the annual reactive power revenue requirement of Black Hills Wyoming, LLC, on file with FERC in Docket No. ER09-1627-000 ($260,384). Accordingly, as of January 14, 2011, the Aggregate Annual Reactive Revenue Requirement under this Schedule 2 is $2,652,386, provided that the Aggregate Annual Reactive Power Revenue Requirement may change if the annual reactive power revenue requirements of other generators with annual reactive power revenue requirements on file with FERC for the provision of reactive power to the Transmission System change or if other generators file annual reactive power revenue requirements with FERC that are recoverable under this Schedule 2. The Transmission Provider will post on OASIS the annual reactive power revenue requirements of other generators with reactive power revenue requirements on file with FERC for the supply of reactive power to the Transmission System, as identified in Section 2(c) above. Not later than thirty (30) days after receiving (1) notice that such a generator with an annual reactive power revenue requirement on file with FERC for the provision of reactive power to the Transmission System has filed a request to change its annual reactive power revenue requirement, or (2) notice that an additional generator has filed an annual reactive power revenue requirement with FERC for the provision of reactive power to the Transmission System, the Transmission Provider will post to OASIS the generator’s requested annual reactive power revenue requirement. Not later than thirty (30) days after receiving notice of FERC's order on such filing, the Transmission Provider will update its posting on OASIS to reflect FERC's disposition of the generator’s filing and identify the annual reactive power revenue requirements of other generators with reactive power revenue requirements on file with FERC for the supply of reactive power to the Transmission System. If the Transmission Provider files an amendment to this Schedule 2, it will update it to identify the then-current annual reactive power revenue requirements of other generators with reactive power revenue requirements on file with FERC for the supply of reactive power to the Transmission System. 3. Transmission Provider will derive $/kW unit rates through the following formula and apply that unit rate to each kW of Reactive Billing Load of each transmission customer taking service under this Schedule 2: $/kW Annual Charge = (Aggregate Annual Reactive Revenue Requirement ? Summed Reactive Billing Loads)
$/kW Monthly Charge = $/kW Annual Charge ÷ 12 $/kW Weekly Charge = $/kW Annual Charge ÷ 52 $/kW Daily Charge Off-Peak = $/kW Annual Charge ÷ 365 $/kW Daily Charge On-Peak = $/kW Annual Charge ÷ 312 $/kW Hourly Charge Off-Peak = $/kW Annual Charge ÷ 8,760 $/kW Hourly Charge On-Peak = $/kW Annual Charge ÷ 4,992 4. For purposes of calculating monthly charges under this Schedule 2, “Reactive Billing Load” will be determined on a kW-month basis. In this determination, items (a) through (e) below are to be multiplied by the monthly charge developed in Paragraph 3: (a) kW-months of Network Integration Transmission Service shall represent actual load on the Transmission System at the time of the Transmission Provider’s Monthly Transmission System Peak; (b) kW-months of Point-to-Point Transmission Service, for which the duration of service is one month or longer, shall represent (one) 1 month multiplied by the kW of Reserved Capacity on the Transmission System by a Schedule 2 customer; (c) kW-months of weekly Point-to-Point Transmission Service shall represent the kW of Reserved Capacity multiplied by the number of weeks of service and by the ratio 12/52; (d) kW-months of daily Point-to-Point Transmission Service represents the kW of Reserved Capacity multiplied by the number of days of service, and by the ratio 12/365 in the case of Off Peak service and by the ratio 12/312 in the case of On Peak service. The total demand charge in any week, pursuant to a reservation for daily delivery, shall not exceed the rate specified in subsection (c) above times the highest amount in kilowatts of Reserved Capacity in any day during such week. On-Peak is for service provided Monday through Saturday and Off-Peak is for daily service provided on Sunday and holidays (New Year’s Day, Martin Luther King Jr. Birthday, Memorial Day, Independence Day, Labor Day, Columbus Day, Veterans Day, Thanksgiving Day, and Christmas Day); and (e) kW-months of hourly Point-to-Point Transmission Service represents the kW of Reserved Capacity multiplied by the number of hours of service, and by the ratio 12/8760 in the case of Off-Peak service and by the ratio 12/4992 in the case of On-Peak service. On-Peak Hours are the hours between 7:00 a.m. and 11:00 p.m. Monday through Saturday, and Off-Peak Hours are all other hours. For the avoidance of doubt, the total demand charge in any day pursuant to an hourly reservation shall not exceed the applicable daily rate times the highest amount in kilowatts of Reserved Capacity in any hour in such date, and the total demand charge in any week pursuant to a reservation for hourly service shall not exceed the weekly rate times the highest amount in kilowatts of Reserved Capacity in any hour during such week. 5. The formula set forth above will be applied through the following process: Not later than September 30 of each year, Transmission Provider shall determine the next calendar year’s projected Summed Reactive Billing Loads. Such projected load shall serve as the rate divisor for purposes of deriving charges to be billed for Schedule 2 service provided during that calendar year. Consistent with the requirements of Attachment H and as part of the annual rate determination process governed by Attachment H, by October 30 of each year, Transmission Provider will hold a meeting, to which its customers and representatives of the SDPUC and WPSC will be invited, to identify the applicable Aggregate Annual Reactive Revenue Requirement and to explain the projected aggregate Reactive Billing Load, the resulting $/kW-month rate, and the resulting rates for weekly, daily, and hourly services.
Not later than June 1 of each year, Transmission Provider will calculate and post to its OASIS the actual Summed Reactive Billing Loads on the Transmission System during each month of the preceding calendar year and the difference between that actual amount and the previously projected amount for the same calendar year. If the Aggregate Annual Reactive Revenue Requirement has changed during that calendar year pursuant to a Section 205 or 206 rate change accepted by FERC, the actual and differential load information will be broken out by the period(s) before and after the effective date(s) of such change. From such calculations, the Transmission Provider will calculate a true-up adjustment designed to reverse any under-collection or over-collection of the revenue requirements identified in Sections 2 and 3. The true-up adjustment and related calculations shall be posted to the Transmission Provider’s OASIS no later than June 1.
Interest on any over-recovery of the revenue requirements shall be determined based on FERC’s regulations at 18 C.F.R. § 35.19a. Interest on any under-recovery of the net revenue requirement shall be determined using the interest rate equal to Black Hills Power's actual short-term debt costs capped at the applicable FERC refund interest rate. In either case, the interest payable shall be calculated as follows. The interest rate will be determined using the applicable rate averaged across the sixteen (16) months, January of the year prior through the April of the year in which the true-up occurs. That interest rate will be applied, with quarterly compounding, to the principal amount (i.e., the over or under recovery in the net revenue requirement) for the eighteen (18) months during which that over or under recovery exists.
The true-up adjustment shall be paid in full in July. The amount on any over or under recovery shall be allocated to the customers based on actual billing determinants for the preceding year.
